<P>(As Augustus said of Rome, I found it of Brick, I left it of Marble! so the Rebuilder of London might as properly say, I found it of wood and clay, I left it of brick and stone.) 
<P>Injuries have often made way for better fortune: many places have fallen and have arisen greater and loftier than before. Timagenes, the enemy of the City of Rome herself, said thou though the burning of her would at <num value="1">first</num> cause sorrow, yet he knew that she would arise again fairer than she had fallen. (<hi rend=italics>Seneca's Epistles</hi>, <num value="92">92</num>.) 
<emph>The Measures of the Greatest of the Ancient Columns.</emph>

<P>The whole height of the Column of the Emperor Antonmus at Rome, is <num value="230">230</num> Roman Palms; the diameter of the shaft is <num value="16">16</num> Palms <num value="4">4</num> inches, (<num value="172.50">172 1/2</num> feet high, <num value="12">12</num> feet <num value="3">3</num> inches diameter, English.)&mdash;<hi rend=italics>Reliqui&aelig; Antiqu&aelig; Urbis Rom&aelig;</hi>, by Bonavent. ab Overbeke. Amsterd. <datestruct value="1708--"><year reg="1708">1708</year></datestruct>, fol.&mdash;The whole height of the Column of the Emperor Trajan at Rome, from the base to the statue of St. Peter upon the top, <num value="193.50">193 1/2</num> Roman Palms; its diameter near the base contains <num value="16">16</num> Palms, <num value="1">one</num> inch and a half, (<num value="145">145</num> feet <num value="1.50">1 1/2</num> inch high, <num value="12">12</num> feet <num value="2.50">2 1/2</num> inches diameter, English.) In like manner, then, in the diameter of this Pillar, a whole Palm is to be accounted for every <num value="9">nine</num> inches contained in it.&mdash;N.B. The Roman Palm contains <num value="9">9</num> English inches. The Column at Constantinople called the Historical, or of the Emperor Theodosius, or the Arcadian, is <num value="147">147</num> feet in height according to the computation of Peter Gillius. (<hi rend=italics>De Topographia Constantinopoleos.</hi> Lugd. <datestruct value="1561--"><year reg="1561">1561</year></datestruct>. <num value="4">4</num>to. 
